The story behind the workshop ↓

“Look at them. They may not know who they are yet. But hold the crown above their heads and dare them to grow into it.”

— Howard Thurman

I’m Jeff Livingston. I’ve spent 25 years in education strategy — figuring out how to make learning systems actually work for students. I built this workshop because I watched brilliant students treat the most powerful learning tool ever created like a vending machine.

I had three people in mind when I built this.

High School
Ethan — NYC
College
Ethan — Morehouse
Career
Jaylen — Amherst

A high schooler thinking about engineering. A college sophomore at Morehouse who uses ChatGPT but hasn’t built a system yet. A recent Amherst grad heading to law school who doesn’t know how much the gap between what he thinks AI can do and what it actually can is about to matter.

High School / Ethan: Ethan is a bright high school junior thinking about his future college career in engineering. He knows AI exists. He doesn’t yet know what it can do for him.

College / Ethan: Ethan is a brilliant sophomore at Morehouse College thinking about business and public service. He uses ChatGPT. He hasn’t built a system yet.

Career / Jaylen: Jaylen is a recent graduate of Amherst College preparing for law school and his career beyond. The distance between what he thinks AI can do and what it actually can is about to matter professionally.

This workshop is 24 minutes. Four modules. No theory for theory’s sake — just the protocols, tools, and mental models that separate students who use AI from students who are transformed by it.

— Jeff Livingston

The Tool Ecosystem

Last updated: February 2026

Every tool below has a free tier or a student discount. The gap between free and paid is narrowing fast.

Start Here
Google NotebookLM
Free

Source-grounded synthesis, study guides, audio overviews, flashcards, and probing questions — all anchored to YOUR sources, not the internet. Upload your PDFs, lecture notes, and readings. This is where Protocols 2, 3, and 4 from the workshop come alive.

Tier 1: $0 (Free)
ChatGPT Free
GPT-4o access, Canvas for interactive editing. The free tier now includes the model that was $20/month two years ago.
Free
Google AI Pro
Full Gemini Pro access. Free for students with .edu email. Check current offer deadline — don’t sleep on this.
Free (student)
Perplexity Pro
AI-powered search with source citations. Free Pro access via student verification or referral program (up to 24 months).
Free (student/referral)
Elicit
AI research assistant for academic papers. Find relevant papers, extract claims, build literature reviews.
Free
GitHub Copilot
AI pair programmer in VS Code. Free for verified students via GitHub Education. Only relevant if you write code.
Free (student)
Tier 2: $20–$50/month
Claude Pro (Opus 4.6)
The most sophisticated reasoning model available. Superior thinking partner for intellectual sparring. If you can afford one paid subscription, consider this one.
$20/mo
ChatGPT Plus
GPT-4o with Thinking mode, higher limits. Pay only if you’re hitting free tier caps regularly.
$20/mo
Grammarly
AI writing assistant with grammar, tone, plagiarism checking. Useful but not essential if you’re strong in writing.
~$30/mo
Tier 3: $50+/month
Cursor Pro
VS Code fork with deep AI integration. Free student plan available for 1 year. The upgrade from GitHub Copilot for CS majors.
~$20/mo (free student plan)
Jobscan + Upplai
ATS resume optimization, keyword matching. Not needed until you’re actively applying for jobs.
$20–$50/mo

Two years ago, the free tier of AI tools was barely functional. Today, the free versions of ChatGPT, NotebookLM, and Google AI Pro are more powerful than the paid tiers were in 2024. The gap between free and paid is narrowing, not widening. Start with $0. Upgrade only when you’ve outgrown what’s free.
